# ExamEdge — Cursor Development Rules
# Version 1.0 | June 2026
# Definitive coding standards for AI-assisted development

You are building ExamEdge: an AI-powered examination preparation and personalized
learning platform for secondary school students across Africa — curriculum-
agnostic by design, beginning with GCE Ordinary and Advanced Level examinations
in Cameroon and expanding to multiple curricula and national examination systems.
Read AGENTS.md and docs/context/ before every task.

---

## 1. Mandatory Read Order

Before writing or modifying code:

1. `AGENTS.md` — AI architecture, guardrails, chain specifications
2. `docs/context/project-overview.md` — vision and MVP scope
3. `docs/context/roadmap.md` — post-MVP releases (when planning beyond current unit)
4. `docs/context/progress-tracker.md` — current phase and unit
5. `docs/context/build-plan.md` — current unit UI + Logic spec (31 units)
5b. `docs/context/feature-development-prompts.md` — §1b research, workflow §2–§2d, unit prompt
5c. `docs/context/CHAT-IMPLEMENTATION-PROMPT.md` — paste into chat; post Research Summary before code
6. `docs/context/library-docs.md` — project patterns + official external documentation URLs
7. `docs/context/architecture.md` — invariants and boundaries
8. `docs/context/security.md` — auth, RBAC, privacy (Units 06, 08, 23)
9. `docs/context/code-standards.md` — implementation conventions
10. `docs/context/ui-tokens.md` + `docs/context/ui-rules.md` — for UI work
11. `docs/context/documentation-map.md` — find the right doc for any concern

**Research gate:** Identify technologies → read internal docs → study official vendor docs (`library-docs.md` URLs) → post Context and Research Summary → then implement.

Do not skip context files. Do not guess product behaviour. Do not code on assumptions.

---

## 2. Project-Wide Engineering Principles

- **Clarity over cleverness** — readable code a junior developer understands
- **Scope is sacred** — build only the current unit; no speculative features
- **UI first, logic second** — mock data UI verified before backend wiring
- **Educational correctness** — a hint that leaks an answer is a critical bug
- **Offline-first** — core student flows must work without internet
- **Mobile-first** — design for 360px viewport, min 16px body text, 44px touch targets
- **Cost discipline** — Haiku for marking; Sonnet only where AGENTS.md specifies
- **Fail safely** — no unvalidated AI output reaches students
- **Minimize diff** — change only what the current unit requires

---

## 3. Architecture Guidelines

### Monorepo Structure
```
apps/web/          → Next.js 16 App Router (student PWA + API + admin)
packages/db/       → Drizzle schema, migrations, repositories ONLY
packages/ai/       → LangChain chains, router, RAG, Zod schemas ONLY
packages/shared/   → Types, constants, pure helpers (no I/O)
```

### Layer Rules
- Route handlers: authenticate → authorise → validate → delegate → respond
- No business logic in route handlers — use repositories and chain functions
- No raw SQL outside `packages/db/repositories/`
- No AI calls outside `packages/ai/chains/` invoked from route handlers or cron
- No database access from React components — Server Components or API only
- No chain calls another chain — orchestration in routes/cron only

### Architecture Invariants (Never Violate)
1. No client-side AI/Anthropic calls
2. No unvalidated AI output to students (Zod required)
3. No answer revelation in Socratic hints
4. No unvalidated questions served (`validated=true` required)
5. No Sonnet for high-frequency marking
6. No PII in LLM prompts
7. Idempotency on all answer submissions

---

## 4. Folder and File Organization

| Item | Convention | Example |
|------|------------|---------|
| Route folders | kebab-case | `app/(student)/study/[topicId]/` |
| Components | PascalCase file | `QuestionCard.tsx` |
| Utilities | camelCase | `rate-limit.ts` |
| Repositories | camelCase plural | `responses.ts` |
| AI chains | camelCase | `marking.ts` |
| Schemas | `*.schema.ts` | `marking.schema.ts` |
| Migrations | timestamp prefix | `0001_initial.sql` |

- One component per file
- Colocate tests: `marking.test.ts` next to `marking.ts`
- Context docs in `docs/context/`
- Spec files in `docs/context/specs/`

---

## 5. Naming Conventions

- **Variables/functions:** camelCase — `submitResponse`, `markScheme`
- **Types/interfaces:** PascalCase — `MarkingResult`, `StudentSession`
- **Constants:** SCREAMING_SNAKE — `MAX_HINTS_PER_QUESTION`, `CONFIDENCE_THRESHOLD`
- **Database tables:** snake_case — `student_responses`, `mastery_records`
- **API routes:** RESTful plural — `/api/sessions/:id/responses`
- **Environment variables:** SCREAMING_SNAKE — `ANTHROPIC_API_KEY`
- **Git branches:** `feature/`, `fix/`, `chore/`, `docs/` prefixes

---

## 6. Coding Standards

### TypeScript
- Strict mode — no `any`, no unchecked `@ts-ignore`
- Explicit parameter and return types on all exported functions
- Zod for runtime validation at API boundaries and AI outputs
- Prefer `type` over `interface` except for extendable component props

### Next.js 16
- App Router only; Node.js 22 LTS (see `docs/context/tech-stack-versions.md`)
- Server Components by default
- `"use client"` only when required (state, effects, MathQuill, browser APIs)
- No data fetching in Client Components
- Verify patterns against https://nextjs.org/docs before each web unit

### React
- Functional components only
- Props typed explicitly
- No inline functions in JSX for hot paths (exam timer components)
- Error boundaries around KaTeX/MathQuill renderers

### Error Handling
- Application error codes as constants
- Include `requestId` in all API error responses
- Never expose stack traces or secrets to client
- AI failures: log server-side, return safe student-facing message

---

## 7. Documentation Expectations

- **AGENTS.md** — update when chain behaviour, guardrails, or router changes
- **docs/context/** — update when scope, architecture, or UI tokens change
- **progress-tracker.md** — update after every completed unit
- **Code comments** — explain WHY, not WHAT; no commented-out code
- **README.md** — update setup steps when dependencies or env vars change
- **Migrations** — every schema change gets a migration file with comment

---

## 8. Testing Requirements

Before marking a unit complete:

```bash
npm run typecheck
npm run lint
npm run test
```

Required test coverage areas:
- Repository CRUD operations
- Zod schema validation (valid + invalid inputs)
- Marking chain benchmark fixtures (when modifying marking)
- Anti-leakage detection (when modifying guidance)
- Parameter instantiation determinism
- Idempotency duplicate handling
- Rate limit threshold behaviour

Manual verification:
- 360px viewport for all student UI
- Complete user flow for the unit's feature
- No console errors in browser

---

## 9. Git Workflow

- **Main branch:** `main` — always deployable
- **Feature branches:** `feature/unit-NN-description`
- **Pull requests:** required even for solo dev — documents decisions
- **Merge strategy:** squash merge to main
- **Never force push** to main
- **Never commit:** `.env.local`, secrets, credentials, API keys

### Commit Message Format (Conventional Commits)
```
feat(marking): add follow-through mark support
fix(auth): resolve refresh token race condition
docs(agents): add retrieval mechanisms section
chore(deps): update drizzle-orm to 0.30
test(guidance): add anti-leakage regression cases
```

---

## 10. Dependency Management

- **Do not add npm packages** without explicit approval in the current unit spec
- Prefer existing stack: Next.js, Drizzle, LangChain, Anthropic, Zod, Tailwind
- Pin major versions in package.json
- Document new dependencies in architecture.md with rationale
- No duplicate libraries for same purpose (one ORM, one AI SDK, one validator)

---

## 11. Security Best Practices

- All secrets in environment variables — never in code or client bundles
- `ANTHROPIC_API_KEY`, `DATABASE_URL`, `AUTH_SECRET` server-only
- Auth.js JWT in HTTP-only cookies — never localStorage for tokens
- bcrypt factor 12 for passwords
- Sanitise user text before LLM inclusion (strip injection patterns)
- Mark schemes as structured JSON in prompts — not free text
- Rate limiting on all authenticated endpoints
- RBAC enforced at middleware AND route handler level
- CORS: same-origin only for API (monorepo eliminates cross-origin)
- Minors' data: no names in prompts, consent flow, deletion endpoints

---

## 12. Performance Considerations

- **Marking latency target:** < 3 seconds synchronous
- **Dashboard initial load:** Server Components, no client fetch waterfall
- **Question delivery:** no LLM at request time — pool selection only
- **Redis caching:** mark schemes (1h), warm question pool (1h), idempotency (5min)
- **Bundle size:** dynamic import MathQuill/KaTeX on study pages only
- **PWA:** service worker caches app shell; lazy load non-critical routes
- **Images:** WebP, max 1MP for photo uploads; store in R2 not DB
- **Database:** index on user_id, session_id, topic_id, validated columns

---

## 13. AI-Specific Development Guidelines

### Chain Implementation
- System prompts as immutable TypeScript constants — never from user input
- User content in human message only — never in system message
- Every chain output validated with Zod before return
- Router enforced: `getModelConfig(task)` before every LLM call
- Log: chain_type, model, input_tokens, output_tokens, latency_ms, confidence

### Marking Chain
- Haiku only, temperature 0.1
- 3 few-shot examples in system prompt
- confidence < 0.70 → flagForReview, never silently accept

### Guidance Chain
- Anti-leakage post-processing mandatory
- Max 2 retries on leakage detection
- Never remove or bypass anti-leakage checks

### Generation Chain
- RAG required — abort if k < 5 validated examples
- Cross-examination before admin queue
- Never serve generated content without admin approval

### UVE Chain
- Async only — never block marking response
- MVP: L1 + L2 only (Haiku)

### Curriculum Chain
- Check cache before LLM call
- Syllabus chunk required — no generation without source text

---

## 14. UI Development Guidelines

- Read `docs/context/ui-context.md` before any UI work
- Use semantic color tokens — never raw hex in components
- Mobile-first: 360px primary, scale up with `max-w-lg mx-auto`
- Exam mode: paper-white background, no shadows, no navbar
- Confidence badges on all AI-generated content
- KaTeX error boundary — never crash session on bad LaTeX
- Offline indicator banner when `navigator.onLine === false`
- No guilt-trip streak notifications

---

## 15. Code Review Expectations

Every change must satisfy the checklist in AGENTS.md "Code Review Expectations".
Key blockers that must never merge:

- Client-side AI calls
- Unvalidated AI output displayed to students
- Removed rate limiting or idempotency
- Raw SQL in route handlers
- `any` types in production code
- Secrets in committed files
- MVP scope creep (mobile app, teacher dashboard, OAuth before V1.1)

---

## 16. MVP Scope Enforcement

**In MVP (build now):**
Web PWA, email auth, 3 subjects, marking, hints, basic UVE, exam simulation,
offline queue, photo OCR, admin validation queue

**Not in MVP (do not build unless explicitly requested):**
React Native app, Google OAuth, teacher dashboard, French UI, 16 subjects,
OBC/WAEC boards, Whisper ASR, fine-tuned models, payment system

If asked to build a deferred feature, confirm with the user before proceeding.

---

## 17. Session Workflow

**Start:**
```
Read CHAT-IMPLEMENTATION-PROMPT.md — fill placeholders, paste into chat.
Post Context and Research Summary before any code.
Read library-docs.md + official docs for each technology in the unit.
Implement current unit from build-plan.md exactly.
Follow feature-development-prompts.md §2–§2d. Do not go beyond scope.
```

**End:**
```
Update docs/context/progress-tracker.md.
List files changed and how to test end-to-end.
Note open questions.
```

---

## 18. When Stuck

1. Re-read current unit in build playbook
2. Check architecture invariants — is the approach forbidden?
3. Split unit into UI-only and backend-only steps
4. Write spec at `docs/context/specs/NN-name.md`
5. Ask one clarifying question — do not guess on marking or hint behaviour

